Turkey is widening its diplomatic horizons
Long before Turkey tried to join the European Union, the European powers were eager to penetrate deep into the Turkish hinterland.
On the eastern part of the Bosphorus, perhaps 20 steps into Asia, lies one of the most beautiful relics of this failed imperial ambition.
The Hydarpasha railway station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in the Neo-Renaissance style.
At least that’s what the tour guides tell you.
The building stands between the end of the platforms with a tower on each of its corners looking at the world like some German provincial municipalities.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is slightly decaying.
But once inside the ticket office from the vaulted ceiling, there is no doubt about the magnitude of the undertaking of what was the westernmost passage.
The station was opened in August 1908 by a German consortium, the Anatolia-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, a laggard to the imperial game, wanted to realize its ambitions to dominate the Middle East by means of this railway that ran to Damascus, Baghdad and beyond in what is now Saudi Arabia.
But Germany’s imperial ambitions sank during World War I.
Its railways were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular Arabs.
Its isolation from the surrounding region, generated by the icy borders of the Cold War, has passed.
British and dominating forces advanced out of Egypt and pushed the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there was bad news for Hyderpasha station, too.
In 1917 an ammunition train exploded destroying its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then it has slowly gone into disarray, largely surpassed by history.
But nowadays, this railway outlet to Anatolia and all points to the east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight Turkey's increasingly larger diplomatic horizons.
The ruling Justice and Development Party – the AKP – has created a whole new foreign policy for the country.
Its isolation from its surrounding regions, generated by the icy borders of the Cold War, has passed.
Now there is a new commitment policy.
Notably, the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions of Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To estimate the parameters of this new foreign policy, I boarded the sleeper car for the Turkish capital Ankara, to visit one of the main foreign policy experts of the AKP, the Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning – about ten and a half hours later – after a jolt race along the tracks that produced the old-world rhythms of the famous documentary The Night Mail, I arrived in the Turkish capital – proposed as a new city for a secular state intent on turning its back on its Ottoman past.
But the AKP with its well-known Islamic roots represents an exemplary shift in Turkish consensus.
He suggested some suspicions in the West, most notably in Washington.
A taxi takes me to the AKP headquarters, an ultra-modern structure of stone and steel - built ad hoc - in a developing suburb, surrounded by built-up shopping malls and power bakeries, where managers in business suits - both men and women - meet to make early-morning contracts.
Suat Kiniklioglu could be a center-right politician from almost any other political party in Europe.
Full, tie, I'm sure he also had a Blackberry.
“The purpose of the foreign policy party now is to reintegrate Turkey with its closest neighbors.
The Cold War was an anomaly," he says.
Turkey has been cut off from its hinterland.
Today it has to look east and west at the same time.
This was not the case for either of them.
It must be both.
"But surely at some point," I ask, "will Turkey be forced to decide?"
"Turkey," he says, "doesn't want where to face that choice."
Then he points out a point that almost everyone with whom I have spoken here has recited from memory: the ties of the EU not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus, and all around the Black Sea, are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, the message seems to be, the whole of Europe can metaphorically travel those railway lines east through Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha station, after another blank night, I think of those two German gentlemen Herr Ritter and Herr Conu who had looked at this building built 100 years ago.
How surprised they would have been to find that Europe’s Middle Eastern ambitions can now largely be in Turkey’s hands.
And while I wait at the terminal for the ferry that takes me back through the Bosphorus, I remember that in those days Turkey was always called "the sick man of Europe".
At that time, at least, there seemed to be no doubt as to which continent to make demands on this fascinating country.
Vernon Handley and William Woodruff
Mark Brown writes: As Guildford's music director since 1962, Vernon "Tod" Handley (obituary, September 11) had been in charge of the Guildford Philharmonic Orchestra and the choir.
As a member of his music scheme for the municipality, the following year he founded his wonderful youth choir, Proteus.
They were supposed to be under-21s, but by the time Proteus sang their final in 1979, many of us were in our twenties — we just refused to give up the choir.
The name "Proteus" (the mythological being-changing) represented the goodwill of the choir and the ability to face everything that the music presented to do, both madrigals and Messiaen, without accompaniment or with the whole orchestra.
The musical versatility produced by such a young choir was often amazing, always exciting, and it was all because of that man’s inspiration and enthusiasm for music that remained absolutely constant through the years.
How often we were told by Tod to “let the music speak for itself.”
He said, "The composer knows what he wants.
It's all there, in the music.
So sing it!"
His technique in the use of the wand was absolutely clear and precise, though never dictatorial or flowery.
Whatever the musical standard was, it was making it more and more elevated.
John Frayn Turner writes:
If you were to appoint a conductor as a knight, it would have been Vernon Handley.
I knew him very well during the two decades he conducted the Guildford Philharmonic from 1962 to 1982.
Over the past 40 years and more I’ve watched more than 100 of his concerts and I can honestly say that I’ve never been at odds with one of them – and many times inspired by them.
Tod Handley had that rare combination of personal greatness and modesty.
He hated conductors who, in his words, simply “run around the world one or two well-known workhorses.”
He will be missed by so many of us.
William Woodruff
