Morgan Stanley has specified that the global operation would be carried out on the basis of an average price of 29 dollars to title, or a percentage inferior to its current course of 28%.
At around 5 p.m., however, Morgan Stanley fell 6.79% to $23.07.
“This strategic alliance represents an important opportunity to accelerate Morgan Stanley’s transition to a bank holding company,” said John Mack, CEO of Morgan Stanley.
Morgan Stanley adopted this new statute last week, which should allow it to differentiate its shares by passing them under the control of the Federal Reserve.
Its alliance with the MUFG also confirms that the current financial crisis is forcing the biggest names on Wall Street to adopt a much more cautious attitude than previously assumed.
The modalities defined Monday also show that in recent days the agreement has been modified: last Monday, Morgan had simply announced the sale of 20% of its shares to the Japanese giant for a sum equal to 8.5 billion dollars.
A week ago, in Tokyo, Toshihide Mizuno, executive director of MUFG, explained: “We thought that our shareholding would be composed exclusively of ordinary shares.
But considering the current state of the world economy and the market, we have chosen to minimize risks and protect ourselves."
Based on the weighted average price, MUFG will obtain Morgan Stanley securities at a price below their book value of 7%.
And the transaction would result in an investment of at least 20% of the equity on a diluted basis.”
The agreement provides that MUFG will be able to convert half of its preferential shares into ordinary shares in one year if, during a given period, the latter are exchanged more than 50% below the conversion price set, i.e. around $47.
Morgan Stanley assures that the capital contributed by MUFG would allow it to seize investment opportunities, strengthen its balance sheet and increase its liquidity.
A spokesman for the group, however, declined to elaborate on the strategic plans of the two new allies.
After MUFG’s investment, Morgan Stanley should therefore establish a Tier One solvency ratio of about 15%, one of the best in the industry.
Morgan said it had "clearly" eased its balance sheet from the end of August.
The last few weeks have put a strain on the group, which has seen the value of its shares halve while the cost of insurance against risks has soared.
The cost rebounded on Monday but remained at a high level, around 12%.
Goldman Sachs, the only other “surviving” Wall Street investment bank after the collapse of Bear Stearns and Lehman Brothers and the takeover of Merrill Lynch, announced last week that it had collected $15 billion, in part from Warren Buffett’s Berkshire Hathaway group.
Rafael Correa in Quito, this Monday.
To establish a republic on the basis of socialism in the 21st century.
This is the joint project of Venezuelan Hugo Chávez, Bolivian Evo Morales and Ecuadorian Rafael Correa.
On Sunday, following the example of colleagues and friends, it was the latter who gave voice to the draft of a new Constitution.
According to the official results, 64% of voters voted "yes" in the referendum, on a basis of 80% votes.
According to these results, the "no" votes were 28%, while 7% of the votes were null and 0.7% were blank ballots.
For the draft constitution to be adopted, it would have to get half of the votes plus one.
On Sunday, two polls conducted at the exit of the polls and an estimate of a non-governmental organization had announced an overwhelming victory of the "yes", placing it between 63% and 70%.
Rafael Correa claimed victory in his draft constitution on Sunday and Monday.
The "Constitution triumphed gloriously," he had assured, congratulating Ecuadorians in the governorate of Guayaquil, 280 kilometers southwest of Quito.
As always, Chávez and Morales congratulated Rafael Correa, as did his Chilean counterpart Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which took place calmly according to the electoral observation mission of the Organization of American States (OAS), was based on a text of 444 points designed to consolidate the "new socialism" defended by the president.
This draft Constitution consecrates the power of the state over the economy, reserving to it the "development planning" of a country that lives essentially on the oil extraction carried out by large foreign companies and consequently on their currency.
Conceived by Correa, elected in 2006, the project also gives more power to the head of state, who can be elected for two consecutive four-year terms, to have the opportunity to dissolve the assembly.
Correa has already announced his intention to take advantage of this amendment and to re-propose his candidacy for a new term in February 2009.
The Constitution also affirms the free health and education services, which the president has begun to promote in this country of 13.9 million inhabitants, where 50% of the population lives below the poverty line.
It also prohibits the presence of foreign troops, a provision that will end the agreement between Quito and Washington for the use of an Ecuadorian base as a starting point for U.S. anti-drug operations.
The 19 hostages released in Chad
An Egyptian commando launched the assault on the kidnappers of the eleven tourists and their eight companions kidnapped ten days ago.
I'm in Cairo.
The eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian escorts held captive in the desert for ten days were brought back safely to the Egyptian capital on Monday afternoon.
In the morning, they had been freed in Chad by an Egyptian commando.
Apparently fit, the hostages arrived at the military base of Almaza, near Cairo International Airport, around 3:30 p.m., aboard a special plane.
On board a helicopter, they were immediately transferred, without being able to give any interview to the press, to the hospital of Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for analysis.
They are in "good health" and no ransom was paid "to the kidnappers," Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garanna said on the runway.
Kidnapped on September 19 during a 4x4 safari at the foot of Mount Ouanat, bordering Egypt, Sudan and Libya, this group of hostages had been tossed from one hideout to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The group consisted of 11 tourists – five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian – and 8 Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, a border guard and the director of Aegyptous, the safari’s organizing agency.
An Egyptian security official said 30 members of the special forces, aboard two helicopters, had launched the assault overnight, just before dawn.
"There were gunshots, half of the kidnappers were killed, while the others fled," the official said, requesting anonymity.
He explained that 150 members of the Egyptian special forces of the "lightning" unit were sent to Sudan, where they would be supported by German and Italian commandos.
Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini stressed, from Belgrade, the importance of the role of Italian secret agents and special forces.
We have to admit that if we achieved this result it was thanks to the professionalism and efficiency of the men of our secret services, of the special forces," he said, without adding further details.
He also denied paying a ransom.
The day before, the Sudanese patrol army had claimed to have intercepted a 4x4 vehicle in which the kidnappers were located and to have killed six of them, including the Chadian leader of the kidnappers, and to have captured two of them.
According to the army, the kidnappers are linked to a rebel organization in Darfur, the Sudan Liberation Movement (SLA_U), a claim immediately denied by the latter.
Letters- The Silent Majority of Culture
On the front page a debate on the financing of culture on which the current election campaign focuses.
All the better.
But a part of our cultural life is always in the shadows.
Who will speak out to denounce the meager sums granted to small museums, archives, archaeological excavations or national historic sites that are hungry?
What politician will dare remind the federal government that it is neglecting monuments and heritage buildings?
That in Quebec, as in Canada, we do not have real laws that actually preserve our heritage?
Did you know that the French government pays three and a half million euros for the restoration of the castle of Chinon, in the Loire Valley?
To our American neighbors, it is the Constitution that states that the protection of heritage is part of national culture and that the same heritage must be protected by every citizen, by every political authority and by every government department, and all this by common agreement.
In Quebec, at least 40,000 volunteers from the Federation of Historical Societies of Quebec, grouped into 211 societies for the preservation of historical, genealogical, archives and heritage assets, preserve private archives and archaeological sites with four dollars.
It is they who often defend our heritage, who protest with the energy of despair when real estate entrepreneurs and decision-makers attack our forgotten remains and cemeteries with their bulldozers.
When will the right space be given to history and heritage?
Benelux governments nationalize part of Fortis bank
The Benelux states help by partial nationalization the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was the first in trouble in Europe due to the crisis of the American credit market: the three nations will provide 11.2 billion euros to the financial institution - insurance with interests also in Hungary.
The governments of Belgium, Luxembourg and the Netherlands agreed at the highest level over the weekend, also involving the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
In the euro area, the first major crisis in the difficulties facing the international financial market for more than a year is that of Fortis Bank, and from a certain point of view the decisions taken in this regard can set a precedent.
Under the decision taken on Sunday night all three states will hold almost half (49%) of the bank’s share in the country.
The bank will almost certainly sell some of its interests, including first and foremost the assets, especially insurance, of the Dutch ABN Amro acquired a year ago.
Last week, Fortis’ stocks began with a vertical collapse, and serious signs of the institute’s crisis appeared in the second half of the week.
Analysts, however, agree that the bank, with 85,000 employees, is too big to allow it to go bankrupt.
The bank’s shares fell nearly 12% on Friday, the lowest point in 14 years.
Since January, the value of shares has fallen by more than two-thirds.
Considering the current share prices the entire capital value of the group is around 14 billion euros, but according to the bank’s managers this value is not real.
The company’s summit blames the collapse of Fortis shares on the uncertainties of the non-European market due to the acceptance of the US $700 billion plan.
On Monday, the title slowly picked up again.
On Friday Filip Dierckx was appointed the bank’s new CEO.
The financial institution has also sought out private buyers but so far no one has come forward with a deserving offer.
The Belgian government had already assured investors that they should not fear losing money.
The bank's customers did not panic, the branches were not attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis has autonomous subsidiaries and has also acquired leasing companies.
The fox in the chicken coop
In America, life and health insurers, based on people’s medical purchase data, often refuse to enter into an insurance contract.
Privacy experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
“There is a privacy program that the use of prescription drug data depends in any case on the approval of the person concerned.
This program must be in independent hands, otherwise it is like entrusting the chicken coop to the fox," the Washington Post writes, quoting Richard Dick, author of the program, to follow prescriptions for drugs.
Insurance companies make the insurance rate and the amount due in the event of claims dependent on the health status of the potential customer and if they consider the risk too high, they do not take out insurance.
Once upon a time the client had to undergo a medical examination and the contract was concluded only after the result of the examination.
Dick 10 years ago invented a much cheaper procedure: based on the customer's identification code, you can easily get information from pharmacies about which medicines he has bought in the last year and a half and from this the program shows which diseases he suffers and in which health conditions he is.
For example, if you regularly purchase large amounts of cholesterol-lowering products, this means that the level of fat in your blood is practically incurably high and is classified in the highest risk category.
In the market there are various versions of the program, some also determine the risk multiplier, the insurer therefore in addition to paper work does not remain much, even if there are small difficulties.
Among the cons is that some medicines are usable for several purposes, e.g. some compounds are usable against migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
The latter, from an insurance - commercial point of view, is valid as a risk increase factor, the first two are not.
For the request and data processing, separate companies have been formed and, before obtaining the necessary information from pharmacies, they ask for the patient's approval.
Now the authorities force them to do so even if they have not imposed fines for negligence so far.
Some companies have also recently processed the results of laboratory tests and linked them to drug consumption data in order to provide a more accurate picture of the health status of patients.
More and more companies have access to data and, at the same time, the control of use will be increasingly difficult.
There is a separate privacy law but its validity extends only to health services and insurance.
In front of Congress there is a bill that gives the authorities control competence to companies specialized in data service.
Richard Dick admits that it is not enough: for this reason he has developed a program that connects the forwarding of data with the express approval of the person concerned.
Another issue is that the person concerned cannot so much deny approval because otherwise the insurers do not enter into the contract.
So then in the end the hens are entrusted to the clemency of the fox.
Marseilles menu global
India and the European Union to double trade
Since the European Union and India are partners that trade mostly with each other, the agenda of the ninth summit has also been dominated by this theme, in addition to all other global problems.
Today there will be a Franco-Indian summit that will deal first and foremost with cooperation on atomic energy.
The European Union recognizes that India is becoming a major democratic power that should be given more voice in international affairs, but member states have yet to decide whether or not to support New Delhi as a permanent member of the UN Security Council.
So we did not insist on this issue at the ninth summit held yesterday in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, as the EU's rotating president, José Manuel Barroso, the Commission's president, and Javier Solana, the High Representative for Foreign Affairs, received Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they agreed to double trade in five years, i.e. increase up to <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>100 billion.
Considering that between 2000 and 2007 trade in goods rose from 25 billion to 55 billion, this is not an overly ambitious goal.
As a result, they have legally unified the 26 bilateral civil flight agreements, so that air traffic can also start in the future.
India would like to sign the free trade agreement with the EU by the end of 2009.
Sarkozy has promised to speed up the deal.
The aim is to balance because while the EU is India’s top trading partner, New Delhi is only ninth among the EU’s partners.
The summit paid attention to global affairs.
To the situation in Afghanistan and Pakistan and to terrorism, the latter condemned in all its forms by both sides, and urged the convening of a UN conference.
They urged the conclusion of the Doha Trade Round, although both sides played a role in the failure of this.
The EU has confirmed its persistence in the energy and climate programme, meaning it would like to reduce emissions of harmful substances by at least 20% by 2020.
India also agrees on this, as well as on the fact that a global pact should be concluded at the climate conference scheduled for next year and that greenhouse gas production should be reduced by 50% by 2050.
They also want to curb rising food prices and have supported the convening of an international meeting to examine the financial crisis.
