Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared a year ago, has been found.
The wreckage of the plane of Steve Fossett, the billionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007 while flying over the Nevada desert, has been found.
The debris was found on a plateau at an altitude of 3,000 meters, in the Sierra Nevada area of Mammoth Lakes, on the border between California and Nevada.
Inside the plane, however, there were no human remains.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson said: "The plane was located, we sent a team, and now we have confirmation that this is exactly the one Steve Fossett was flying on the day it disappeared."
The sheriff said no human remains were found either in the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old billionaire was reported dead in February.
The U.S. Bureau of Transportation Security (NTSB) said that a team of investigators was dispatched hours after the wreck was spotted, which then identified the device: it was the Bellanca 8kcab, missing since September 3, 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington, Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, in California, not far from the Nevada border, some of Fossett’s personal belongings were found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
These are two documents under the name of Fossett, both issued by the Federal Aviation Administration of Illinois, cash and a sweatshirt.
Fossett's search was halted a month after his disappearance.
The billionaire had earned a place in history thanks to a long string of records.
In 2002, on the sixth attempt, he became the first man to complete the world tour on a balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later he had travelled the world by plane and without a stopover.
Among his many records, he also flew at 15,445 meters above the Andes, but with a co-pilot.
Glk, the ad you don't expect
An out of the box SUV with an original design and well defined by sharp lines, wide surfaces and sharp corners.
It is this, in summary, Glk the latest born among the "compact" offroads of the star house with which Mercedes-Benz has tried to give a breath of freshness in this sector.
Due to its contents outside the traditional canons, the communication that will accompany the launch of the Suv Glk, available at the Mercedes-Benz showrooms from October 17, will also be unexpected and unconventional.
Thus, the advertising hype that will accompany the debut of the new car will initiate an unprecedented mode of communication also through a futuristic 3D poster campaign, used for the first time in Italy by an automotive brand.
A project of maxi-posters, divided into three different phases, which will dominate the central shopping street of Milan, Corso Como, until November 15.
The first phase of this new type of communication will begin with the presentation of the car in stereoscopic vision and thanks to special glasses distributed near Corso Como it will be possible to see the new SUV in almost real size and in three-dimensional format.
